<subSubSection id="48C86517FF8BFFBE768A55FDFA67D6B7" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" type="key">
<keyStep id="BB262E39FF8BFFBE768A55FDFA6BD5E7" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<paragraph id="006D369CFF8BFFBE768A55FDFA6CD54F" blockId="41.[151,1436,226,665]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<materialsCitation id="B0BA3CC1FF8BFFBE768A55FDFA6CD54F" location="Floristic Province" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="California">
<keyLead id="BB2395A9FF8BFFBE768A55FDFA6CD54F" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
1 Prothoracic hypomera with deep antennal cavities that are clearly limited posteriorly, and completely contains the antennae while in repose (
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE77F9541AFD99D532" box="[484,617,261,284]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40" captionStartId="44.[151,269,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[274,1314,462,1635]" captionTargetId="figure-290@44.[210,1377,456,1639]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40. Ventral surface of pronotum. 39. Phloeodes diabolicus; 40. P. plicatus. 41. Lateral view of P. diabolicus hypomeron." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230765" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230765/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Figs. 39, 41</figureCitation>
); elytra usually with at least partially visible velvety arcuate patches; elytra with elevated sculpture reduced, at most to single weak median nodule at start of apical declivity. 
<collectingRegion id="C216F87EFF8BFFBE72CC5437FACDD511" box="[1233,1341,296,319]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">California</collectingRegion>
<location id="050D6047FF8BFFBE735E5437FED9D54F" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:887B878AFF8BFFBE768A5588FA67D6B7:050D6047FF8BFFBE735E5437FED9D54F" name="Floristic Province" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" stateProvince="California">Floristic Province</location>
. 
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE772E5455FE41D54F" box="[307,433,330,353]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–38" captionStartId="42.[151,269,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[369,1234,178,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-151@42.[320,1266,132,1672]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 35–38. Dorsal habiti. 35. Phloeodes diabolicus, California, San Diego Co.; 36. Phloeodes diabolicus, California, Napa Co.; 37. P. plicatus, California, Los Angeles Co.; 38. P. venustus, Costa Rica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230761" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230761/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Figs. 35–36</figureCitation>
<emphasis id="32A6EA8EFF8BFFBE77AA5455FB6BD54F" box="[439,1179,330,353]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">...............................................................................................................</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="C7D24D1FFF8BFFBE72835455FA6CD54F" authority="(LeConte)" baseAuthorityName="LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[1182,1436,330,353]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Phloeodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diabolicus">
<emphasis id="32A6EA8EFF8BFFBE72835455FAD8D54F" box="[1182,1320,330,353]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">P. diabolicus</emphasis>
(LeConte)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="006D369CFF8BFFBE768A5472FA6BD5E7" blockId="41.[151,1436,226,665]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<keyLead id="BB2395A9FF8BFFBE768A5472FA6BD5E7" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
- Prothoracic hypomera with deep antennal cavities that are incomplete and not limited posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE72FD5472FADFD5AA" box="[1248,1327,365,388]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40" captionStartId="44.[151,269,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[274,1314,462,1635]" captionTargetId="figure-290@44.[210,1377,456,1639]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40. Ventral surface of pronotum. 39. Phloeodes diabolicus; 40. P. plicatus. 41. Lateral view of P. diabolicus hypomeron." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230765" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230765/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
), or broad shallow depression (
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE77BD548FFE1FD589" box="[416,495,400,423]" captionStart="FIGURES 42–46. 42" captionStartId="46.[151,269,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[419,1208,199,1583]" captionTargetId="figure-177@46.[267,1319,150,1624]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURES 42–46. 42. Lateral view of P. venustus hypomeron. 43. Ventral view of tarsus of P. venustus. 44–46. Male genitalia. 44. P. diabolicus; 45. P. plicatus; 46. P. venustus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230767" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230767/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
); elytral vestiture variable; elytra with three distinct nodules at start of declivity, two offset medially, and one laterally....................................................................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="BB262E39FF8BFFBE768A54CAFA67D6B7" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<paragraph id="006D369CFF8BFFBE768A54CAFA6CD61F" blockId="41.[151,1436,226,665]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<materialsCitation id="B0BA3CC1FF8BFFBE768A54CAFA6CD61F" location="Floristic Province" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="California">
<keyLead id="BB2395A9FF8BFFBE768A54CAFA6CD61F" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
2 Prothoracic hypomera with deep antennal cavity that is not limited posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE720554CAFB98D5C2" box="[1048,1128,469,492]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40" captionStartId="44.[151,269,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[274,1314,462,1635]" captionTargetId="figure-290@44.[210,1377,456,1639]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES 39–41. 39–40. Ventral surface of pronotum. 39. Phloeodes diabolicus; 40. P. plicatus. 41. Lateral view of P. diabolicus hypomeron." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230765" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230765/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
); elytral vestiture uniform in coloration from dark red to black; with only three nodules in area of declivity; length rarely over 
<quantity id="C72A9B79FF8BFFBE72C354E7FAD5D621" box="[1246,1317,504,527]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="20.0">20mm</quantity>
. 
<collectingRegion id="C216F87EFF8BFFBE732D54E7FA6CD621" box="[1328,1436,504,527]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">California</collectingRegion>
<location id="050D6047FF8BFFBE76DA5705FE78D61F" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:887B878AFF8BFFBE768A5588FA67D6B7:050D6047FF8BFFBE76DA5705FE78D61F" box="[199,392,538,561]" name="Floristic Province" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" stateProvince="California">Floristic Province</location>
. 
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE778F5705FE2ED61F" box="[402,478,538,561]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–38" captionStartId="42.[151,269,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[369,1234,178,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-151@42.[320,1266,132,1672]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 35–38. Dorsal habiti. 35. Phloeodes diabolicus, California, San Diego Co.; 36. Phloeodes diabolicus, California, Napa Co.; 37. P. plicatus, California, Los Angeles Co.; 38. P. venustus, Costa Rica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230761" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230761/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
<emphasis id="32A6EA8EFF8BFFBE77C25705FB45D61F" box="[479,1205,538,561]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">.............................................................................................................</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="C7D24D1FFF8BFFBE72A45705FA6CD61F" authority="(LeConte)" baseAuthorityName="LeConte" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[1209,1436,538,561]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Phloeodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plicatus">
<emphasis id="32A6EA8EFF8BFFBE72A45705FAD8D61F" box="[1209,1320,538,561]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">P. plicatus</emphasis>
(LeConte)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="006D369CFF8BFFBE768A5722FA67D6B7" blockId="41.[151,1436,226,665]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<keyLead id="BB2395A9FF8BFFBE768A5722FA67D6B7" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
- Prothoracic hypomera with shallow depression, lacking distinct cavity (
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE75DB5722FBE6D67A" box="[966,1046,573,596]" captionStart="FIGURES 42–46. 42" captionStartId="46.[151,269,1620,1644]" captionTargetBox="[419,1208,199,1583]" captionTargetId="figure-177@46.[267,1319,150,1624]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURES 42–46. 42. Lateral view of P. venustus hypomeron. 43. Ventral view of tarsus of P. venustus. 44–46. Male genitalia. 44. P. diabolicus; 45. P. plicatus; 46. P. venustus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230767" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230767/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
); elytral vestiture mottled whitish to black, with velvety spots along suture and on ridges; with three nodules in declivity area and fourth nodule near apex of elytra; length usually over 
<quantity id="C72A9B79FF8BFFBE741C579DFDB9D6B7" box="[513,585,642,665]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" unit="mm" value="20.0">20mm</quantity>
. Central America. 
<figureCitation id="98E92A19FF8BFFBE750C579DFCADD6B7" box="[785,861,642,665]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–38" captionStartId="42.[151,269,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[369,1234,178,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-151@42.[320,1266,132,1672]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURES 35–38. Dorsal habiti. 35. Phloeodes diabolicus, California, San Diego Co.; 36. Phloeodes diabolicus, California, Napa Co.; 37. P. plicatus, California, Los Angeles Co.; 38. P. venustus, Costa Rica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5230761" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5230761/files/figure.png" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
<emphasis id="32A6EA8EFF8BFFBE757F579DFB6BD6B7" box="[866,1179,642,665]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">...............................................</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="C7D24D1FFF8BFFBE7283579DFA67D6B7" authority="(Champion)" baseAuthorityName="Champion" box="[1182,1431,642,665]" class="Insecta" family="Zopheridae" genus="Phloeodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="venustus">
<emphasis id="32A6EA8EFF8BFFBE7283579DFAE2D6B7" box="[1182,1298,642,665]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">P. venustus</emphasis>
(Champion)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
